Taking lung cancer as an example, occupational exposures are estimated to account for 6% of the incidence of lung cancer in developed nations of the Asia–Pacific, and 10% in developing nations;
55
 the attributable risks are higher in men (8% in developed and 12% in developing nations), compared with women (3% and 7%, respectively), reflecting the fact that men work more often in occupations with higher carcinogen exposures.
